nsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"12785","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12785"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.81,0.04,0.02,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5224"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48563"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5224","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5224"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12785"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33485"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"4051"},{"type":"tags","id":"11696"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8869"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9150"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12506"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48563"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 16-year-old girl presents to her general practitioner with a three-day history of intermittent epistaxis. Two weeks ago, she had a \u0027flu-like\u0027 illness for which she took paracetamol. On examination, there are petechiae on her arms and limbs; the rest of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 120 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 5 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4-11)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 10 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150-450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPT 10 sec (10-15)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAPTT 26 sec (25-37)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EReticulocyte 1.2% (0.5%-2%)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELactate dehydrogenase 150 U/L (120-250)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEstimated glomerular filtration rate \u226590 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Drug-induced immune thrombocytopenia","Immune thrombocytopenic purpura","Von Willebrand disease","Aplastic anaemia","Atypical haemolytic uremic syndrome"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe given scenario is highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003EImmune thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP)\u003C/strong\u003E. The pathophysiology is incompletely understood. However, it is thought that platelets are coated with autoantibodies against glycoproteins (e.g., GPIIb/IIIa), which causes sequestration, phagocytosis and early destruction. A common preceding event is viral infection, as seen in this case. Patients commonly present with petechia, purpura, or mucocutaneous bleeding. Since the intrinsic and extrinsic factors are not involved, prothrombin time (PT) and activated partial thromboplastin time (APTT) are not affected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrug-induced immune thrombocytopenia (DITP)\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by drug-dependent platelet antibodies. Drugs such as penicillins, heparin, and quinine can cause DITP, but paracetamol is unlikely to cause it. The thrombocytopenia may be moderate to severe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVon Willebrand disease (vWD)\u003C/strong\u003E is an inherited bleeding disorder (autosomal dominant or recessive) caused by a deficiency or dysfunction of the von Willebrand factor. Symptoms include mucocutaneous bleeding and menorrhagia. A prolonged aPTT and mild thrombocytopenia may also be seen. The degree of thrombocytopenia seen in this case is not consistent with the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAplastic anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is a bone marrow failure syndrome caused by the loss of haematopoietic stem cells. This leads to pancytopenia, which can cause fatigue, infections, bleeding, or bruising. Given the normal haemoglobin and leucocyte count, this diagnosis is unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtypical haemolytic uremic syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a thrombotic microangiopathy caused by abnormalities in the complement pathway. It presents with thrombocytopenia, microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, and acute kidney injury. This diagnosis is unlikely given the normal lactate dehydrogenase and estimated glomerular filtration rate in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Immune thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP) is an immune disorder due to autoantibodies against platelet glycoproteins","Viral infection is a common trigger of ITP","ITP commonly presents with petechia, purpura, or mucocutaneous bleeding"],"references":["Cooper N, Ghanima W. Immune Thrombocytopenia. N Engl J Med. 2019;381(10):945-55.","Bakchoul T, Marini I. Drug-associated thrombocytopenia. Hematology. 2018;2018(1):576\u201383."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33485"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12785"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33485","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33485"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-13T23:02:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-13T23:02:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5224"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48563"}}},"meta